  "prompt": "What are Some interesting facts of Langar at golden temple?",
  "response": "Langar at the Golden Temple, also known as Harmandir Sahib, is a significant aspect of Sikh culture and spirituality. Here are some interesting facts about it:\n\n1. **Historical Origin**: The practice of Langar was initiated by Guru Nanak Dev Ji, the founder of Sikhism, in the 15th century. It was formalized by Guru Angad Dev Ji, the second Guru, who established the first community kitchen.\n\n2. **Free Meals for All**: Langar serves free meals to anyone who visits, regardless of their religion, caste, or background. This embodies the Sikh principle of equality and community service.\n\n3. **Daily Service**: The kitchen at the Golden Temple operates 24 hours a day, serving thousands of people daily. On average, the Langar serves around 30,000 to 50,000 people each day, with numbers soaring to over 100,000 on special occasions.\n\n4. **Vegetarian Meals**: The food served in Langar is strictly vegetarian, adhering to the principle of Ahimsa (non-violence). Meals typically consist of simple and wholesome dishes like dal (lentils), roti (bread), and sabzi (vegetable curry).\n\n5. **Volunteer System**: The service is run entirely by volunteers (known as \"sewadars\") from various backgrounds, who help prepare, serve, and clean up after the meals. This spirit of selfless service is a core tenet of Sikhism.\n\n6. **Mass Production**: The kitchen is equipped to cook in large quantities, with massive cauldrons and industrial-sized cooking equipment. It\u2019s estimated that the kitchen uses around 1.5 tons of flour and over 1 ton of rice daily.\n\n7. **Community Participation**: Langar is a communal effort where people from all walks of life come together to prepare and serve food. This fosters a sense of community and belonging.\n\n8. **Spiritual Significance**: Sharing food in Langar is seen as a way to cultivate humility, equality, and gratitude. It is considered a spiritual practice that brings individuals closer to God and to each other.\n\n9. **Cleanliness and Hygiene**: The Langar kitchen maintains strict hygiene and cleanliness standards. Volunteers wash their hands thoroughly before preparing food, and the entire area is kept clean to ensure the health and safety of all diners.\n\n10. **Global Influence**: The concept of Langar has inspired similar community kitchens around the world, reflecting the universal values of sharing and caring that transcend cultural and religious boundaries.\n\nLangar at the Golden Temple is not just about providing food; it is a profound expression of Sikh values of equality, community service, and spirituality.",
